      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solvers with iterative refinement were employed. Residual norms confirmed convergence to machine precision for all load steps. No divergence or ill-conditioning was detected across the ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was independently reviewed by a second analyst. Boundary condition definitions, material assignments, and contact pair specifications were verified against documented analysis plans. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic isotropic material models are appropriate for the metallic implant components under sub-yield loading. Frictional contact at the screw-rod interface is represented with a Coulomb model, consistent with published literature for titanium-on-titanium contact in spinal hardware."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (elastic modulus, Poisson's ratio) sourced from ASTM F136 titanium alloy specifications and confirmed by coupon testing on lot-matched material. Geometric inputs derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test articles. Uncertainty bounds quantified and propagated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested; sample size is sufficient to characterize construct-to-construct variability. All specimens drawn from the same manufacturing lot and inspected per incoming quality control procedures. Traceability records maintained."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single load level per ASTM F1717 protocol. While temperature, humidity, and actuator calibration were controlled and documented, the absence of multiple load conditions prevents characterization of load-dependent nonlinearity. Achieved gradation 2 is one below the required gradation 3; this shortfall is acknowledged as a residual gap."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) were systematically mapped to the physical test configuration. A parameter equivalency table confirms one-to-one correspondence. Discrepancies in fixation torque were resolved by sensitivity analysis showing less than 1.5% influence on stiffness prediction."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Predicted construct stiffness and yield load were compared against experimental measurements using a validation metric based on the area validation metric (AVM). All FEA predictions fell within the 95% prediction interval of experimental data. Mean absolute percentage error for stiffness was 4.7%; for yield load, 5.2%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield load under ASTM F1717 compression-bending are directly specified in the regulatory submission as the quantities of interest for demonstrating mechanical equivalence to predicate devices. These quantities are clinically meaningful surrogates for implant stability during the bone fusion period."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the ASTM F1717 test configuration that defines the intended use scenario for the regulatory submission. The FEA ensemble was validated against experiments conducted on the same device design, material, and size as the subject of the submission, maximizing relevance to the intended use scope described in the claim and requirement nodes."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed required levels for Model Risk Level 3. The single shortfall in Test conditions (achieved gradation 2 vs. required gradation 3) is bounded by the ASTM F1717 protocol scope and does not materially affect the validity of the stiffness and yield load predictions within the load range of interest. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support the regulatory submission claim. The intended use scope — FEA prediction of ASTM F1717 compression-bending performance for a non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct in adult posterior lumbar fusion — is articulated in the claim and requirement documentation referenced by this assessment.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
